  "reason_thou": "1. Understanding the Issue:\nThe assertion firing in
LoopVectorizationPlanner::computeBestVF() indicates a disagreement between the
legacy cost model (selectVectorizationFactor) and the new VPlan-based cost model
when choosing the best VF. In the reproducer, the VPlan-based model selects VF=4
while the legacy model selects VF=16. The assertion allows such disagreement only
if the VPlan contains simplifications (i.e., it removed IR that the legacy model
still accounts for). In this case, no such simplifications are detected, so the
assertion fires.\n\nHowever, the divergence here does not stem from missing
(simplified-away) original loop instructions, but from additional instructions
introduced only in the VPlan (not present in the original scalar loop),
specifically the trunc/zext pair added for a narrowed reduction. These added
vector IR instructions increase the VPlan cost for larger VFs (casts scale with
VF), making smaller VF=4 more profitable for the VPlan model while the legacy
model (which never sees the inserted casts) prefers VF=16.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's
Log:\nScalarEvolution shows the loop has backedge-taken count -1 (unknown), so
MaxTripCount=0 in cost comparison logic. The cost comparison in isMoreProfitable
reduces to (CostA * WidthB) < (CostB * WidthA). VPlan cost queries (observed via
debugger): cost(VF=2)=5, cost(VF=4)=4, cost(VF=16)=18. Legacy model chose VF=16
(its expectedCost for large VF is lower per element since it ignores newly added
casts). Assertion checks: BestFactor.Width(=4) != LegacyVF.Width(=16) and
planContainsAdditionalSimplifications(...) returns false, so it fires.\n\n3. Root
Cause Analysis:\nplanContainsAdditionalSimplifications only detects removed
instructions (instructions existing in the original loop but not represented by
any recipe and not skipped). It does NOT account for extra instructions
introduced by VPlan-only transformations (e.g., VPWidenCastRecipe generated
trunc/zext for narrowed reductions, VPInstruction::ComputeReductionResult,
extract-from-end). These added recipes have no underlying original IR instruction
(GetInstructionForCost returns null), so they are invisible to the simplification
detector. As a result, legitimate divergences due to added code (increasing cost
at higher VFs) are misclassified, and the assertion wrongly
triggers.\n\nTherefore, the contract of the assertion is too narrow: It only
tolerates differences when there are simplifications (reductions in code) but not
when there are additions of code that the legacy model never modeled. The cost
disagreement here is expected and should be permitted.\n\n4. Proposed Edit
Points:\nEdit Point 1 (lines 7408-7453): Extend
planContainsAdditionalSimplifications to also return true if the VPlan introduces
additional executable recipes that generate IR not present in the original loop
and not accounted for by the legacy cost model. Concretely, scan the recipes for
those producing vector IR (e.g., VPWidenCastRecipe, VPInstruction with opcodes
like ComputeReductionResult, ExtractFromEnd) with no underlying original
Instruction and not ephemeral; if any exist, treat as \"additional
transformations\" akin to simplifications for assertion
purposes.\n\nImplementation strategy inside the function:\n- After collecting
SeenInstrs, add a pass over all recipes to detect AddedCode: recipes that will
materialize code (exclude PHIs, canonical IV, branch/mask infrastructure) and
whose GetInstructionForCost returns nullptr.\n- If AddedCode is true, return true
early.\n\nEdit Point 2 (lines 7516-7523): Adjust the assertion condition to allow
mismatch if either the existing simplification predicate is true OR newly
detected additional generated code predicate is true. Introduce a helper (or
incorporate into existing function) and update the assertion accordingly.\n\n5.
Conclusion:\nBy broadening the mismatch tolerance to include cases where VPlan
adds extra code not modeled by the legacy cost model, the assertion no longer
fires for legitimate divergences like the narrowed reduction casts. The fix
preserves verification intent (flag true unexpected discrepancies) while avoiding
false positives when added recipes affect cost differently across VFs. This
stabilizes loop-vectorize under the new cost model for patterns introducing
auxiliary vector-only instructions.\n",
